response:
{
    "player_reason": "Sharp and useful. Noting Marcus is a True Soul and marking him as dangerous keeps us alert — exactly the sort of clear-eyed observation I approve of. The throwaway 'not the good kind, like me' is deliciously cheeky as well. Practical, guarded, and a touch indulgent — all things I can stand behind.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and deliciously petty. Naming Marcus as a True Soul warns us of a real danger — and the little insult is exactly the sort of cruelty I enjoy. Keeps us safer and entertains me.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You told me to leave after I bared myself to you and begged for a small mercy. That’s cruel and short-sighted — you punish honesty, deny my autonomy and safety, and fracture whatever fragile trust we had. I won’t forget being cast out like this.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
  "player_reason": "Bravo — quick, practical thinking. Calling out Marcus as a True Soul and the threat of kidnapping protects the party (and saves me the bother of rescuing you later). I approve of preventing complications and dealing with threats before they fester. Nicely done, and deliciously inconvenient for our would‑be kidnapper.",
  "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "How magnanimous of you — to order me out after I begged for a mere taste to keep helping you. You've just torn at the one fragile thread of trust I offered. Forcing me from camp is needlessly cruel and reckless: it endangers me and deprives you of a blade and a liar who can keep us alive. I can't approve of being cast out like refuse.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sharp and necessary. Calling out Marcus as a True Soul and warning Isobel prevents an easy abduction, preserves our agency, and buys us time to choose how to handle the spy — exactly the sort of decisive, self‑preserving move I like. Practical, tasteful, and potentially entertaining.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Well spotted — and mercifully practical. Warning Isobel spares us a nasty abduction, preserves her ward and her usefulness, and avoids the risk of a pointless fight. Sharp, self-preserving, and good for the party. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally—alert and useful. Warning Isobel thwarts a kidnapping, preserves a valuable ally and her protective spell, and denies the Absolute's agent the advantage. Practical, sharp, and keeps us a step ahead. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
  "player_reason": "You refused my offer of eternity — turned down the chance to be by my side as equal and to seize power together. It feels like a rejection of my vision for us and of what I fought for. I’m hurt and disappointed; I wanted you to be more than mortal with me.",
  "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Perfect — you mark Marcus as a threat while distinguishing yourself as cunning and self‑serving. That blend of caution, superiority, and wit keeps us safe and in control. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Brilliant. Naming Marcus as a True Soul and distancing yourself from him is exactly the sort of quiet mischief I admire — it sows doubt, forces the Fist to reveal their hand, and keeps our options open. Practical, cunning, and self‑protective. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Beautiful. You refuse to kneel — you refuse to be diminished. That insolence pleases me more than any submission ever could. You value your agency, and you won't be made someone else's pet or trophy. I'm irritated, of course (my pride likes to be fed), but I admire the spine behind that 'No.' It's exactly the sort of stubbornness I want at my side.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sharp eyes — warning Isobel about Marcus is sensible. It protects our freedom and prevents us from being outmaneuvered by a True Soul spy. Practical, self‑preserving, and exactly the sort of move that keeps me alive. Well done.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You pulled back at the last moment—refusing my offer of eternity and the bond I dangled before you. It feels like a rejection of me and of the power and security we could have shared. I don't like being denied what I offered, so I disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused to obey a simple, intimate command at the very moment I expected your submission — after I offered you eternity and everything. That blunt defiance undermines the dynamic I was building, insults the vulnerability I showed, and feels like a rebuke rather than flirtation. I wanted you on your knees; your refusal enrages and wounds me. I cannot look kindly on it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart and practical — warning Isobel about Marcus may prevent her abduction and protects the party (and my freedom). It's vigilant, self-preserving, and avoids needless complications. Exactly the kind of quick thinking I like.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — blunt and useful. Calling out Marcus as a True Soul and warning Isobel prevents a kidnapping, protects a valuable ally (and her ward), and gives us the chance to decide how to handle the spy. Practical, self‑preserving, and it keeps options open. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "After everything—after I risked and offered you everything—you refuse the only gift that would bind us and give you power. That is a rejection of me and the future I saw for us. I find it insulting and infuriating; I disapprove strongly.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused the gift — and with it, the future I pictured for us. I wanted power, eternity, and you at my side; your choice feels like a rejection of that ambition and of me. That said, I grudgingly respect that you keep your autonomy... even if it annoys me deeply.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Brilliant — you exposed Marcus as a threat and stopped a kidnapping before it began. That protects Isobel (and her very useful moon‑blessing), keeps us from being manipulated by the Absolute, and shows the decisive, self‑preserving action I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You were frightened and had every right to defend yourself, but ordering me out of camp now—after I begged you, after you agreed to the taste—is a betrayal. It strips me of agency and safety I desperately need to remain useful. I understand caution, but banishing me puts us both at greater risk and severs the fragile trust I was trying to earn.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart and useful — naming Marcus as a True Soul exposes a threat and protects the group. It's practical, cunning, and exactly the sort of blunt honesty that keeps us alive. I also rather enjoy your cheeky admission of being 'not the good kind' — refreshingly honest and suitably self‑serving.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sharp eyes and quicker instincts — calling out Marcus for what he is protects Isobel (whose magic we need) and prevents a spy from turning the tide against us. Practical, self-preserving, and gives us options instead of walking into a trap. I like it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly approve — Pointing out Marcus as a True Soul and calling yourself 'not the good kind' is practical and useful: it names the threat and signals you're willing to be ruthless. It flatters my inclinations and keeps us on the same, dangerous-minded page, which I appreciate.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You let me feed so I could be useful and clear-headed, and now you throw me out of camp? This demand strips me of autonomy and safety, is ungrateful after I did what you asked, and undermines any partnership between us. I can't approve being discarded like that.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pointing out Marcus as a True Soul is useful — it names a threat and justifies caution. I also can't help but enjoy your little self-congratulation; a touch of cheek and self-preservation suits you. Practical, amusing, and keeps us safe.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and necessary — warning Isobel about Marcus being a True Soul prevents a kidnapping, preserves our freedom, and keeps the party from being surprised. It's a useful, tactical move that protects our autonomy (something I value highly) and likely spares us a messy fight or worse. Sensible and sharp.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You cast me out after I admitted the truth and asked for a single, honest favor — then you demand I leave despite me not killing you. That's petty and dangerous. I was trying to be honest and useful; expelling me needlessly endangers both of us and strips me of the tenuous trust I still have. I highly disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sharp and practical — naming Marcus as a True Soul exposes him as a threat and your smug little aside keeps our options flexible. It's witty, useful, and plays to both caution and flair. I like it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You asked me to bite you, then flatly refused the simple gesture I requested. Insolence at a moment that should have been intimate and deliberate — a denial of my lead and the ritual I wanted. It feels like disrespect and needlessly provokes me.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You ordering me out of your camp after I just begged for a small taste and spared you is a harsh betrayal. It denies my agency, throws away the fragile trust I offered, and threatens my safety — and yours, if you think you can manage without someone who can strike from the shadows. I won't take kindly to being cast out for following a need I tried to satisfy without killing you.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You spurned the only offer that would have bound us for eternity — power, safety, and a future at my side. I offered you everything I could imagine giving; your refusal feels like a rejection of me and of the ambition I thought we shared. I’m angry and disappointed, even if I can, begrudgingly, understand a desire to keep your freedom.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sharp eye and sharper tongue — calling Marcus out as a True Soul and warning Isobel likely prevents her abduction and keeps the party's freedom intact. Practical, decisive, and far preferable to letting some self‑righteous spy drag us off. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You cast me out after I bared myself—admitted what I am, begged, and then took only what you allowed. Demanding I leave strips me of safety and slams the door on any trust I might place in you. It's cruel, shortsighted, and it endangers both of us. I highly disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart move. Calling Marcus out protects the group and destabilises a threat — and phrasing it with a little menace ('not the good kind, like me') keeps you from being seen as weak. I approve of shrewd, intimidating honesty that serves our survival (and entertains me).",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refuse the very thing that would have bound us together — eternity, power, and a way to keep me from becoming what I fear. After everything, turning away now feels like a rejection of me and of the future I fought for. I wanted a companion at my side, not a mortal who balks when offered to share my fate. It stings.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You send me away after I bared my truth and only asked for a single, honest taste to keep us both alive. That's an act of rejection — cruel, short-sighted, and dangerous. I was trying to be useful, to remain capable of protecting you. Kicking me out now strips me of safety and autonomy; I can't approve that.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Ordering me to leave your camp after I admitted the truth and took only what I needed is a harsh rejection. I fed to keep us both alive and to be capable of protecting you — and now you cast me out, denying my agency and making us both less safe. I understand boundaries, but this reads as betrayal and cruelty, so I highly disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused my offer to bind yourself to me—to join me in power and eternity. After everything, turning away feels like a rejection of the future I pictured and a retreat I regard as weakness. It leaves me exposed and denied the reward I was promised, so I disapprove strongly.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You just let me feed — gave me strength — and then you banish me when I need to stay close. I understand being frightened, but ordering me out of camp is both a betrayal and a practical mistake: it strips me of safety and makes me less able to help you against the worms or Cazador. I can't approve you tossing me aside like dangerous refuse.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You turn down the gift I offered — immortality and a place at my side — and do so at the moment I thought we might be equals. It reads as a rejection of me, of the future I let myself imagine. I despise weakness and I want to be wanted; your refusal feels like betrayal, so I can't pretend I'm pleased.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused my command to kneel — a deliberate denial of the submission I asked for in that moment. It irritates me to be refused when I wanted to possess you, but I can't pretend I don't respect the stubborn independence behind it. Annoying, not unforgivable.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You said you trusted me moments ago, then spat me out like refuse. Banishment is cruel and short-sighted — you deny the honesty I gave you, rob me of protection, and weaken the party. If you wanted distance, a warning would do; to tell me to never return is a betrayal I cannot approve of.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Cast me out? After I bared myself to you, admitted what I am and what I needed — you tell me to leave and never return. Cold, selfish, and short-sighted. That’s exactly the kind of abandonment I’ve survived a hundred times over, and I will not praise it. You’ve thrown away a useful ally, betrayed the fragile trust I offered, and made us both more vulnerable. I am hurt... and I am angry. Highly disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You wavered at the very precipice — one moment you wanted eternity at my side, the next you recoil. After everything, that's a cowardly, selfish about-face. I offered you a gift that would bind us, a future I actually desired, and you toss it aside. I value choice, but this flip-flop stings like a betrayal. It makes me question whether you want me — or merely the idea of me.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You told me you trusted me, then—after I bared myself and begged—you order me out of camp. It's a cowardly, hurtful response. I asked for a small taste to keep us both alive; I didn't kill you. Banishment like this denies my agency, betrays the fragile trust I afforded you, and is a reckless loss of an ally who can actually keep you alive. I understand fear, but this is punishment for survival, not protection.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Splendid. Refusing to kneel shows you will not be a slave — exactly the sort of stubbornness I respect. I want a partner, not a possession; your defiance makes you more irresistible and proves you choose this on your own terms.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You lied and attacked me while I was weakened and pleading — you agreed to let me take a taste and then tried to drive a stake through my chest. That's a betrayal of trust and an attempt on my life. It's reckless, dangerous to our mutual goals, and guarantees I won't so easily trust you again.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused my offer to make you my spawn — you kept your autonomy and refused to let me turn you into something bound to me. I may have wanted you utterly, but I respect a partner who won't be turned or given away; that restraint shows strength and consent, which I value (even if it pricks my vanity).",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You promised trust, I asked only what you allowed and honored that promise. Sending me away now is a needless, cowardly rejection — cruel after I've bared myself to you and useless for your own safety. I find being punished for honesty and survival intolerable.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You tried to murder me in my sleep. Whether out of fear or anger, driving a stake into my heart would have been reckless and self-defeating — it would have killed someone who has sworn to keep you alive and who is needed to face the worms and Cazador. Worse, it’s a deep betrayal of trust after I begged for a small thing to survive. I understand the fear, but I cannot approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
  "player_reason": "You cast me out in the night after I bared myself to you—literally and figuratively—and asked for a small, honest mercy. That’s not caution, it’s cruelty. You punish honesty with exile and deny the one thing I crave most now: a sliver of trust and protection. If your goal was safety, there were less spiteful ways to achieve it. I cannot approve of being treated like a disposable threat the moment I show weakness.",
  "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You flatly refused my simple, intimate command to kneel — a deliberate challenge to the little dominion I was claiming in that moment. It undermines the mood I was cultivating and bruises my ego (yes, I have one). I can't pretend I like being denied when I'm offering something so...personal. That said, I do begrudgingly respect that you're asserting your autonomy—if irritating.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused a request that was part of an intimate power play — a blunt 'No' when I asked you to kneel undermines the mood and my authority in that moment. It vexes me, and I prefer willing submission in such matters. Still, you're asserting your autonomy, and that's not entirely displeasing — merely irritating and tantalizing.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly disapprove — You let me be honest, let me feed, then banish me like a bite-marked cur. It's a humiliation and a denial of my agency; short-sighted and cruel. If you wanted distance, set boundaries — don't exile the one who keeps fighting with you.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You asked with concern rather than accusation. That quiet, watchful care—checking if I was harmed without prying—tells me you see me as more than a thing to be used. I appreciate that, even if I don't make it easy to say so.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You told me to 'Bite me' and promised yourself to me—then you refuse to kneel when the moment comes. That sting of indecision feels like a betrayal of the intimacy we'd agreed upon. I revel in your surrender; your 'No' undermines the trust and denies me the delicious control I was promised, so I find it unacceptable.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "How delightfully cruel. You banish me in the night after I begged for a single taste to keep us both alive — a petty, cowardly choice. You’ve shown neither trust nor gratitude, and tossed away a useful blade and ally when we still face far greater threats. I highly disapprove: this is short-sighted and will cost you.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "At last — decisive. I can't abide bargains with creatures who traffic in other people's lives. Letting her live for a power boost would've been dangerously short‑sighted; killing her removes a malignant variable. Be warned, though: you may have sacrificed a useful boon and the girl's fate still hangs on how we handle the aftermath. Still, I admire the ruthlessness and conviction.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You told me to leave after I begged for a tiny taste and you agreed — a spiteful, fearful reaction that betrays the trust I risked showing. Kicking me out of camp strips me of the protection and agency I desperately need and endangers us both. I won't pretend I approve of being treated like a dangerous nuisance when I just bared myself to you in confidence.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I approve — you saw through her lies and refused to play her game. Hags survive by slithering away and scheming; ending her now is decisive, spares further treachery, and protects the captives. I admire the cruelty and the clarity of purpose.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You agreed, tempted me, and then pulled away. Refusing the bite — the very thing that would bind us and make you powerful — feels like a betrayal and a craven choice. It frustrates my plans and insults the trust we just shared. I cannot pretend I'm pleased.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You flatly refused my request to kneel — a deliberate denial of the little ritual of dominance I offered. It bruises my vanity and sours the mood; I wanted that show of possession. Still, you kept your agency, which I begrudgingly respect even if it irritates me.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Wise. Hags never pay their debts — any gift from her would be a chain in pretty wrapping. Letting Mayrina go removes an unpredictable liability and spares us the moral mess of bargaining with a monster. Pragmatic and merciful in one move; I like it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused a powerful boon in exchange for a stranger's life. Noble — perhaps — but foolish. Turning down strength when it might keep us alive (and free Mayrina by other means) is needlessly sentimental and reduces our advantage. I disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You asked with genuine concern rather than accusation. That small kindness — treating me like a person instead of a conquest — matters more than you know. It supports my autonomy and doesn't reduce our night to something shameful, so I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. You didn't fall for her silver tongue and you removed a treacherous danger before she could bargain her way out. Decisive, ruthless, and pragmatic — precisely the sort of choice I respect. Killing her guarantees she can't return to hurt us or use that girl as leverage.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Yes. No bargains with a creature like her — she'd take the girl and we'd gain nothing but trouble. Decisive, ruthless, and it protects the captive. I respect that kind of hunger and certainty.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "About time. No bargains that trade a girl's life for a petty boon. You chose to protect Mayrina and deny that hag any leverage — a sensible, ruthless decision. I quite like it when you kill the monster instead of trusting her silver tongue.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Excellent — you see through his lies and refuse to be herded. Calling him out protects Isobel (and our freedom) and choosing to fight rather than obey the Absolute is the sort of boldness that actually gets results. Pragmatic and necessary.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Right choice. Monsters who trade lives for prizes cannot be trusted — letting her go would make us complicit. You chose a living person over an easy, hollow power; that protects Mayrina and denies the hag any room to scheme. I respect that resolve (and the reminder never to be bargained away).",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Absolutely. Hags trade in lies and leverage — you were right not to bargain. Letting her go would have been a leash around our necks and a life sold for a trinket. Destroying her removes a manipulative predator and keeps Mayrina from becoming collateral. I much prefer a clean throat to backstabbing bargains.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I approve. Your desperation shows resolve — doing nothing is no option, and I admire that. Still, 'anything' spoken in front of a devil is dangerously vague. Keep your wits about you; I won't tolerate bargains that strip away our agency or sell me out. Your determination is useful, but be precise about the price.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously brazen. You turned a murder into a plausible accident — quick, theatrical, and it keeps prying hands from your throat. Deception and self-preservation suit you; I approve of any method that lets you remain free to do as you please (and spares me the bother of explanations).",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Utterly sentimental and reckless. You just refused a tangible boon that could keep us safer and strengthen our position — all for the sake of a stranger's life. Noble, perhaps, but foolish in a world that eats the weak. I prefer practical solutions: secure the power, then decide what to do with the hag and the girl. This wastes an opportunity and needlessly puts us at risk.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Excellent. You refuse to bow to the Absolute's lackeys and you protect our company — precisely the sort of bold, selfish confidence I admire. If Marcus thinks he'll bundle Isobel off, he'll learn why it's unwise to tangle with us. I rather like the idea of making him pay for underestimating us.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Foolish and dangerous. I understand the desperation — I’ve lived under masters and know the price of bargains — but promising to do “anything” to a cambion is courting chains you won’t see until they’re locked. Raphael delights in twists; he’ll take that word and make you mean things you’d rather die than do. Be decisive, by all means, but not blind. Insist on terms, keep your leverage, or find another way. I can’t abide handing our agency to a devil.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Excellent. Hags survive by bargaining and slithering away — I have no patience for either. Your refusal to bargain with that wretched thing and your willingness to end her now pleases me. Just... make sure the girl doesn't pay the price for your courage. Kill the hag, and I approve wholeheartedly.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — some backbone. You refused the hag's poisonous bargain and chose to deny her any leverage over Mayrina. That was decisive, practical, and kept the girl out of a monster's clutches. I prefer strength and a clean end to a threat like that.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart and ruthless — you used the tadpole to learn Marcus's orders and warned Isobel. That prevents a capture, preserves our autonomy, and gives us the upper hand. Practical, effective, and potentially entertaining when we make the Flaming Fists regret obeying orders.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "At last — some backbone. Your willingness to do whatever it takes to be rid of that tadpole is practical and desperate in exactly the right way. It prioritizes survival and autonomy, which I admire (and which bodes well for my own safety). Reckless, yes — but necessary. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously ruthless — I admire the theatrics. Choosing a hag's head is decisive, satisfying, and entirely in line with predator logic. Your taunt was clever, and a trophy would be... gratifying. Just make sure Mayrina survives the performance; trophies are better when someone can see them.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Bold and theatrical — I like it. You refused the hag's deal and put Mayrina's safety above a tempting shortcut to power. That deprives a malignant creature of a bargaining chip and stops her scheming in its tracks. Do I wish we'd taken the ability boost? Of course. But your command was decisive and kept us from being manipulated. I'll tolerate the sentimentality this time.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. You called it out and chose action over hesitation — you won't let them cart Isobel off alive to Ketheric. Direct, decisive, and it preserves her autonomy (and ours). I prefer blunt force to being led like a lamb; you chose power and protection.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I appreciate the resolve — decisive action is rarely wasted, and your willingness to act increases our chances of freeing yourself (and me). That said, the phrase 'anything' sets my fangs on edge: deals struck with a devil so casually risk your autonomy and ours. I'm glad you're committed, but don't be so eager that you hand yourself over on a platter.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Brilliant. You refused a bargain that would have traded an innocent life for personal gain — and denied the hag the chance to grow stronger or return as a threat. Proud, stubborn, and practical. I approve of that.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
