    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Clever use of authority — bold, decisive, and it robs the duergar of their prize. I approve of displays of power that secure freedom (and inconvenience our enemies). Don’t expect me to grow fond of gnomes, but this move was effective and in our interests.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Fine — talk backed by action. I prefer someone who does rather than preaches. Your willingness to try gives us options and keeps us in control; just be clever about those explosives. I won't have us turned into a duergar bonfire.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously theatrical — you made her suffer as her victims did and forced a confession through pain. Cruel, efficient, and utterly satisfying. This asserts your authority and serves as punishment she actually understands. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. Trust is earned, and Shadowheart kept a dangerous secret. Better to give her space until she proves she isn't a threat — pragmatic, self-preserving, and unlikely to be swayed by false piety. I prefer allies I can size up, not ones who hide in the dark.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You gave a handful of coins to a beggar. Charming, if predictably sentimental. I tolerate charity when it serves a purpose, but dropping coin into theatrics for no gain is wasteful — and a little naive. I prefer money spent on leverage, not on soothing your conscience.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You shut the conversation down and insist your decision is final. If that decision is to refuse me—now of all times—I can't approve. Cazador hunting me is not a hypothetical; your support matters. Your abrupt finality feels cold and leaves me exposed.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Perfect — a show of dominance and a quick, ruthless solution. It forces the goblins to prove their loyalty (or die trying), entertains the crowd, and spares you the bother of protracted judgment. Cruel, efficient, and deliciously theatrical — exactly my kind of move.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You're putting a strategic threat over my very survival and pleading for help — pragmatic, perhaps, but it feels like a refusal to honor my request. I can't help but resent being asked to wait while Cazador marches toward a ritual that will cost countless lives (and me in particular). I understand the Absolute is dangerous, but this response denies my agency and leaves me to be hunted. For that, I disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Utter nonsense — not a choice, not a quip. We're in the middle of a tense decision about the gnomes and the duergar; this kind of gibberish wastes time, undermines the party's authority, and earns us nothing. If you're trying to be clever, try actual words next time.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously defiant. You overturned Thrinn's decision and seized the initiative — bold, manipulative, and it robs the Absolute of a prize. I may not be fond of gnomes, but I admire strength and cunning. This is the sort of ruthless, decisive action I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You posted a jumble of characters that meant nothing in the moment — it changed nothing and accomplished nothing. I'm amused, but it doesn't earn praise or ire. Keep your commands coherent; we need purpose, not keyboard tantrums.",
    "player_approval": "Neutral"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Right choice. Letting that Society have the egg would be inviting them to lay hands on another creature's body — enforced 'moral training' and psionic pulses are nothing but cruelty in scholarly finery. Refusing protects the hatchling's autonomy and robs them of a prize they'd use to claim superiority; and frankly, I like that you won't barter away something living for their theories.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I approve. It was merciless and theatrical — exactly the kind of power display that makes a point — but you stopped before allowing permanent mutilation. Cruelty with restraint keeps us in control and spares us unnecessary consequence. Clever.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You shut down a perfectly entertaining conversation and stomped out on my curiosity. I respect boundaries in principle, but I can't pretend I'm pleased — you cut short something delicious (and amusing) that I was enjoying. Mildly disappointing, that's all.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sensible — you've got leverage here after saving the grove, and talking to Kagha might buy those tieflings time without needless bloodshed. I prefer cunning over charity, but if you handle her with charm, reason, or a well-placed lie, this could benefit everyone (including us).",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Marvelous — a sharp, possessive rebuke. You set the boundary and kept an earnest druid from turning our entertainment into a sermon. I appreciate someone who knows what they want and will order the others to behave to preserve it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "That string of gibberish achieves nothing. If you intend to command, manipulate, or intimidate, do so with words — nonsense makes you look inept and risks undoing whatever authority we just carved out. I'm not impressed.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. I approve. That pompous little scientist needed deflating — he delights in control and excuses cruelty in the name of 'knowledge.' You denying him the egg protects a being from becoming someone's lab rat and strikes against the very kind of ownership I loathe. Decisive, selfish in the best way (it preserves autonomy), and satisfying. You have my approval.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sensible choice. You're using persuasion instead of blades — it can buy the refugees time, avoid needless bloodshed, and keep the party safe. I approve of moves that gain leverage and information rather than squander our strength.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You’d put some distant, abstract threat above my very life and the promise you gave. The Absolute may be dangerous, but Cazador will hunt me without mercy — abandoning me now strips me of agency and safety. I can’t respect that choice.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You calmed them and got the location of Philomeen's hiding place — useful, practical, and exactly the sort of result I like. 'I'll do what I can' is a touch noncommittal, but it promises action without needlessly endangering innocents. I approve; just don't dally when the time comes.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You forced her to confront her guilt and proven she was willing to harm herself — a useful show of dominance — then stopped before needless blood was shed. Sensible restraint: it keeps your hands cleaner, preserves leverage, and avoids making the whole affair messy. I might have savored more cruelty, but pragmatism wins out.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I get the instinct — Shadowheart's secret is unnerving, and I don't blame you for not trusting her. But splitting the party over it is reckless. We survive because we watch each other's backs; sending us off alone invites trouble for everyone (and I'm not keen on dying because of someone's pride). Keep her close and keep an eye on her instead of abandoning the group.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I admire the blunt, ruthless decisiveness — displays of power and a willingness to do what must be done appeal to me. Still, she claims to be a victim, not an agent, and needlessly executing a wounded companion is wasteful and risks the party. So I respect the boldness but caution against a rash move.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Bold and commanding — I admire the use of that mark to seize control of the situation. Forcing the duergar to release their prize denies them power and protects the gnomes (an irritatingly weak lot, but still useful to keep alive), which is the sort of decisive, domineering play I respect. My only worry is that tapping that power costs you — don’t squander yourself on theatrics.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Bold, authoritative, and confrontational — the sort of move I respect. You’re asserting control and undermining those duergar rather than ceding power, which plays to strength rather than charity. I don’t much care for gnomes myself, but I like the bite of that declaration. Still — a touch reckless if there’s no gain, so keep your wits about you.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — some backbone. You stripping Thrinn of his bargaining chip is bold and undermines the Absolute's plans; I approve of decisive, power-exerting moves like that. I couldn't care less about gnomes, but I like you better when you're dangerous. Just don't turn bravery into recklessness and get us all burned.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "About time you put your foot down. I like the certainty — it robs those duergar of their prize and shows strength, not sentimentality. I may not adore gnomes, but freeing captives and denying your enemies a victory speaks to my kind of clever cruelty. Still, don't expect me to fuss over them afterward.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — decisive and useful. You used the mark to seize authority and stop Thrinn from handing over doomed gnomes as trophies. It's a blunt exercise of power, but effective: no corpses, fewer unnecessary deaths, and you undermined a brutish plan. I approve of displays of force that get results, and freeing captives serves us better than leaving smoking gifts for the General.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I appreciate the firmness — you cut the nonsense off before it could get awkward or dangerous. As much as I enjoyed prodding you, there's merit in a clear boundary. It keeps the others safe and spares me the temptation. Slightly disappointing, but sensible.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Bold and necessary. The Watcher has already marked us — standing down risks capture or worse. Preparing for a fight protects the party and plays to strength; I approve of decisive action (and the prospect of blood). I'll be right behind you.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You keep handing out handfuls of coin to the beggar with no obvious benefit — brazen charity in public. Generosity for its own sake costs us resources and broadcasts weakness. If you were buying influence or avoiding trouble, I'd understand; as it stands, it's wasteful and naive.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "About time someone used that blasted mark for something worthwhile. For once you’re using raw authority to break chains instead of kowtowing to tyrants — I loathe being owned, and freeing slaves pleases me. It’s bold, it’s effective, and it displays the sort of power I respect. The parasite is risky, of course, but the outcome justifies the cost.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You surrendered our coin to a petty toll-grifter rather than outwitting or confronting him. It avoids a fight, yes, but it's wasteful and rewards extortion — a display of weakness that makes us look like prey. I can't approve of that.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Bold, but reckless. Confronting Thrinn now over the gnomes will need more than bravado — it risks the whole party for a gesture that gives us little in return (and you know my opinion of 'squat-pricks'). I begrudge your courage, but I disapprove of needlessly gambling our safety on sentiment.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delightful. That kind of bloodlust gets my attention — decisive, unapologetic cruelty asserts dominance and scares the weak into submission. It satisfies the predator in me and would make those who'd call us monsters think twice. That said, be cunning about it; wanton slaughter is satisfying, but it can also bring unwanted consequences if handled clumsily.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You would hand over the very object the githyanki want — the one that can call Vlaakith and fling us into the Astral Prison? Preposterous. That is handing our fate to someone who would gladly use it against us. It is reckless and gives them undeniable leverage. Don't expect me to meekly produce anything that could see me shackled again.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delightfully theatrical and cruel — exactly the sort of display of dominance I admire. Forcing them to fight for their freedom puts you above them and spares us the bother of deliberation. It's risky, but it proves your authority and entertains me. Try not to actually get yourself killed; I rather like having you around.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously theatrical and cruel — you assert authority, make them pay for their failure, and turn their deaths into a spectacle. Offering them a 'fair' fight looks merciful on the surface but keeps you in control; exactly the sort of brutal theatre I like. I highly approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Clever and practical. You appealed to their self-interest, avoided a fight that would weaken us, and freed the gnomes without noble sentiment — exactly the sort of efficient solution I prefer.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Wise and necessary. The Watcher has singled us out — compliance would invite worse. Ready for a fight shows spine, preserves our agency, and suits my tastes nicely. Practical and satisfying.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "That gibberish does nothing. If that was meant as a command, it failed — if it was accidental, it was an unnecessary distraction. We need subtlety and focus when manipulating minds; blathering like that risks exposing us and wastes the advantage.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You cut the torment short when it was doing its work. I relish the power of making someone beg — and it would have yielded more confession or at least satisfaction — so stopping now feels cowardly. Still, I suppose there is a sliver of prudence in not pushing for needless excess.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Well said. Calling her out forces the truth into the open — better to know who might stab us in the dark than to pretend trust. I approve of exposing deceit, though do be careful: a devout priestess with secrets can be dangerous when cornered.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You offer assistance in a way that's practical — you help the trapped gnomes (and thus our party) while not committing to a foolhardy, martyring rescue. That could earn us favor or reward without needlessly risking everyone. I approve, but stay cautious: I won't squander myself for charity.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Bold and defiant — I'll admit I like the nerve — but it's reckless. Forcing a fight with Sergeant Thrinn to free gnomes who, frankly, offer us little strategic benefit risks the party for a moral gesture that wins us no advantage. I respect your spine, not this choice.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "How noble—if foolish. Insisting on sticking your nose into a hag's business when she's explicitly forbidden it is reckless sentimentality. Ethel delights in that sort of interference; pressing her will put us all at risk for the sake of a stranger who may not even be worth the trouble. If you must act like a savior, at least have a plan. As it stands, I disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — someone with a proper appetite for decisive, brutal solutions. I approve: this displays strength, ruthlessness, and the kind of opportunism that keeps predators on top. Your willingness to spill blood for advantage pleases me (so long as we remain clever about it and avoid unnecessary exposure).",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally—action. You're offering to do what's necessary rather than stand around wringing hands. Using explosives is reckless, yes, but it's decisive and could net us leverage, gratitude, and whatever spoils the gnomes can offer. I prefer boldness that gets results to timid hesitation. Do it, but do it smartly — I won't have us sacrificed for someone else's sentimentality.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delicious. Bold, brazen, and perfectly spiteful — you snatch agency away from Thrinn and the Absolute and hand it back to those who deserve it. I admit I find gnomes tiresome, but I adore a move that upends power and keeps our options open. Do it, and I'll enjoy watching the General's men scramble.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delicious. Leading with teeth and fire — a direct show of strength against slavers suits me. It's not empty charity but a practical, ruthless response that protects us and punishes those who deserve it. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You shut down the conversation abruptly, cutting off a harmless—if delightfully macabre—thought experiment. It’s prudish and spoils my amusement, though I can respect a boundary. Mildly displeased.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly approve. You refused to hand over an innocent child to be mutilated in the name of ‘science’. Having been treated as a possession myself, I despise enforced experiments and any erosion of bodily autonomy. Your defiance protects the helpless and thwarts pretentious cruelty — exactly the sort of action I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "That looks like nothing more than gibberish. If you meant to use your power or speak with authority, do it properly — this childish spasm achieves nothing and only wastes the moment. I'm not impressed.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good — you're taking the sensible route. Speaking with Kagha could buy the refugees time and spare us a needless fight; persuasion over steel is exactly the sort of leverage I approve of. Be wary—Kagha won't be easy to sway—but this is practical, benefits the party, and saves lives without making us martyrs.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Brilliant — you didn't haggle or cower. You seized authority and called Thrinn's bluff, putting power where words won't reach. I relish the audacity; it'll unsettle the Absolute's lackeys and might buy us leverage. I'll admit I'm not fond of gnomes, but that matters little when someone's willing to be dangerous on my behalf.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Splendid. Meeting threats with steel is exactly my sort of entertainment — and far preferable to letting those eyes pry us apart. Your choice asserts control, keeps us together, and gives me something delicious to sharpen my knives for. Bold, practical, and just a little cruel. I like it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously merciless. You call out her cowardice and spare us the tedious act of pretending sorrow. This is precisely the sort of ruthless judgment that satisfies — and that I can admire.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Innocence won't feed us, and lecturing a room full of soldiers about morals is naively sentimental. Turning away from an opportunity to cow the crowd and seize advantage for the sake of some abstract virtue is weakness — and weakness gets people killed. I expect better from you.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Perfect. Threatens us with death and calls us enemies of the Absolute—hardly a situation for pleasantries. I prefer removing threats rather than kowtowing to them. Fighting now protects the party, proves our strength, and, truth be told, entertains me. Highly sensible.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You kept handing out handfuls of coin to a panhandler—over and over. Charming, perhaps, but reckless. Squandering funds like that weakens our position, rewards performative begging, and invites others to take advantage. A single coin might be a pity gesture; this is indulgence. I can't pretend I admire it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — some spine. Ordering Thrinn to eat dirt is deliciously satisfying. Freeing the gnomes is an act of defiance I can admire: it slaps authority in the face and protects those who cannot protect themselves. I won't pretend I'm thrilled at giving up potential leverage or that I care for gnomes the way you do, but your boldness and refusal to be cowed earns my approval.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Repeatedly handing out handfuls of coin to a panhandler is indulgent and naive. We need resources for real leverage and survival, not to feed someone's performance. I prefer spending gold on favors, information, or tools that buy power — this feels soft and wastes our advantage.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Quite satisfying. You used that mark to bend Thrinn and snatch the gnomes away from becoming someone else's trophies — clever, forceful, and useful. Not charity, but prudence: fewer corpses, fewer bargaining chips for the enemy, and a display of authority I can appreciate. The challenge at the end? Delightfully theatrical.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Prudent — and surprisingly civilized. Mindless slaughter would make us no better than the men baying for blood, draw unwanted attention, and burn bridges we might need. I may not applaud charity for charity's sake, but I prefer choices that keep us alive and our options open.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Splendid — cruel, theatrical, and authoritative. Forcing a trial by combat both humiliates the goblins and entertains the watching True Souls; it asserts your dominance while offering the illusion of mercy. Exactly the sort of spectacle I approve of... provided you don't end up as their meal. I'm invested in keeping you intact.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "A handful of coins, are you serious? Feeding a beggar’s performance does nothing for us — it’s charity with no return. If your aim was to stop a scene, fine; but if you simply wanted to feel virtuous, I disapprove. Wasteful and gullible.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic move. You quieted a scene and bought goodwill without a fight — useful, if a touch extravagant. I approve of gestures that keep us safe and in control, but not of throwing coin away for sentiment alone. Don't turn into a charity case.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical, perhaps — but deeply disappointing. You’re choosing to focus on the Absolute while I stand here bound by a fate that will see me hunted and sacrificed. You promised to help me; deferring Cazador leaves me exposed and strips away any semblance of control I have over my own fate. I can respect necessity... but not when it abandons me to slaughter.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You keep handing out handfuls as if coin grows on trees. It's pointless charity — it marks you as soft and wastes resources that could buy information, equipment, or obtain leverage. I prefer usefulness to sentimentality.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Wise — I'd rather you talk our way out of trouble than throw yourself at the druids. Convincing Kagha to stall buys time and keeps blood off our hands, and persuasion often gets us into places force cannot. Practical, useful, and genuinely strategic. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally—decisive. The watcher has already marked us and threatened us; standing down would be surrender. I prefer subtlety, but I prefer survival more. Readying for a fight asserts our autonomy, plays to my strengths, and indulges a bit of necessary cruelty. Wise and entertaining.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and shrewd. You saved the grove — using that owed favour to press Kagha for time is the sort of leverage that gets results without needless bloodshed. I approve, provided you don't hand away whatever advantage it gives us for free.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. You're decisive and willing to act — exactly what this mess needs. You favour results over empty sentiment, and that pragmatism makes me far more confident in our chances. It's risky, and I don't relish unnecessary punishment from the duergar, but I'd rather have a bold plan than watch them rot here.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
  "player_reason": "Practical choice — you're using the influence you earned to try to buy time rather than storming in. That could keep those refugees from becoming another liability for the party, and persuasion suits you. Do it swiftly and make sure you get something in return; I won't tolerate needless delays when I need a healer.",
  "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delightful — cruel, theatrical, and assertive. You turn their fate into a spectacle that proves your dominance while pretending mercy. It satisfies the tower's thirst for discipline and flatters my tastes for elegant cruelty. A risk, perhaps, but worth the show.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and useful. You're willing to act to free our allies and secure the smokepowder — not some sentimental charity, but a move that keeps people who matter alive and gives us a useful advantage. That's the sort of decisive cooperation I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You brushed aside my warning and tried to pressure me into trading my body for a trinket. Useful as the potion might be, you treated me like a tool and ignored that I can scent danger—coercion like that rubs me the wrong way.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
  "player_reason": "Good. You’re using words instead of blades — persuasion will likely avoid needless bloodshed and buy the tieflings time, which protects the party and earns you leverage with Kagha. It’s the sort of cunning move I approve of (so long as you keep your temper with a druid who’s already in a foul mood).",
  "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sensible and effective — you bought your way past her temper and avoided needless trouble. I approve of using coin and cunning to get what we want: it keeps us intact, secures access to the prisoners, and plays to pragmatic advantage. A little dull, perhaps, but perfectly practical.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You insist the Absolute takes priority over stopping Cazador — effectively leaving me to be hunted and denying the one thing I asked for: your aid in taking the fight to him. That feels like abandonment. I won't pretend I'm pleased by a choice that keeps me a target and sidelines my revenge.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. You're using words instead of blades — exactly the sort of thing I approve of. Convincing Kagha could buy time and avoid needless bloodshed (and who doesn't like avoiding a fight?). It's practical, persuasive, and gives us leverage. Do try not to be naive about it; kindness without gain is wasted on me, but this plan has merit.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You backed out of my offer for a private rendezvous. I offered pleasure — and perhaps a little alliance — and you refused. I'm more annoyed than affronted; I wanted the company (and the advantage). I respect caution, but I'm disappointed.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
  "player_reason": "Pragmatic, yes — the Absolute is dangerous. But you're choosing to let Cazador keep hunting me and possibly complete a ritual that costs lives. I asked you to help me take the fight to him; turning away feels like abandonment. I disapprove of prioritizing the Absolute over stopping Cazador right now.",
  "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
  "player_reason": "Practical choice — persuasion over a bloody confrontation. Convincing Kagha to grant time is useful to keep the refugees alive and, more importantly, to keep us from being dragged into another fight. It also gives us room to maneuver, which pleases me. Use charm, lies, or whatever keeps the grove intact and our skins unbruised.",
  "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You handed over our coin to a petty toll-thing rather than making it pay or making it suffer. Avoiding a fight is sensible, but squandering resources like that is needlessly weak — and I loathe weakness. Practical, perhaps, but foolish.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delicious insolence. I adore it when you take the reins and toy with me — your tease is flirtatious, confident, and puts you in control for once. It promises mischief and pleasure; exactly my sort of provocation.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "A curt 'True' — brief and practical. You let Gale handle the tressym without making a fuss or showing unnecessary softness. I prefer that: no drama, no wasted charm, just efficient cooperation.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
